    </center></div><p><font size="1">Примечания: <br>
    1) представлены арифметические значения по
    5-балльной шкале, <br>
    2) * - Группы существенно отличаются от других
    групп.</font></p>
    <p>&nbsp;</p>
    <p align="center"><a name="Eng"></a><strong><font size="2">SPORT, HEALTH AND BODY CONCEPTS
    IN CENTRAL AND EASTERN EUROPE</font></strong></p>
    <p align="center"><font size="2">J.Mrazek, I.Bykhovskaya, L.Fialova</font></p>
    <p align="center"><font size="2">Deutsche Sporthochschule, <br>
    Koeln, Germany</font></p>
    <p align="center"><font size="2">Rassian State Academy of Physical Education, <br>
    Moscow, Russia</font></p>
    <p align="center"><font size="2">Charles University, <br>
    Prague, Czech Republic</font></p>
    <p style="text-indent: 40; text-align: justify"><font size="2"><b>Introduction.</b> An international research project
    is presented, dedicated to the analysis of sport, health and body concepts in Germany, the
    Czech Republic and Russia. This project, mainly supported by the Club of Cologne, is based
    on two main assumptions.</font></p>
    <p style="text-indent: 40; text-align: justify"><font size="2">First, sport activity, health status and health behavior
    are seen not as independent aspects of individual life styles, but as components of a
    common base, the body concept. The body concept may be defined as the sum of all cognitive
    and emotional representations of one's own body as well as of body related ideals and
    behavioral plans. It is the result of a person's individual experiences with one's own
    body, but probably in more dimensions strongly influenced by the social environment.
    Whereas we have a lot of scientific data about sport activities, health behavior and
    health status, we know little about the concepts associated with these behavioral
    dimensions. But these concepts are of great importance for all attempts to influence sport
    or health behavior of individuals toward a positive direction, because changes of these
    kinds of behavior will be successful only if the concepts are changing too. </font></p>
    <p style="text-indent: 40; text-align: justify"><font size="2">Second, we have only few international comparative
    studies about sport activity and health. These studies usually compare western countries,
    i.e. Germany, United States of America or Great Britain with one another, or they compare
    eastern European countries with one another. We have only little knowledge about
    similarities as well as differences between eastern and western European countries and
    cultures. In the present time which is characterized by political and economical
    transformation processes in Central and Eastern European countries, cultural dimensions
    and social structures are changing too. Simultaneously there are processes of growing
    relations, cooperation and unification. Therefore it seems very important to know and to
    understand better the mutual positions.</font></p>
    <p style="text-indent: 40; text-align: justify"><font size="2"><b>Methods. </b>A questionnaire was developed including
    questions about fitness and sport activity, health status and health behavior, nutrition
    an food and differentiated body concept scales. Three different kinds of samples were
    analyzed: students of physical education, pupils of 11<sup>th</sup> grades and also
    adults. In each country about 400 persons of each group were asked by the questionnaire.
    According to the specific groups some subscales were added to the questionnaire: for the
    students questions about the course of study and evaluation of the study, for the pupils
    questions about their lessons of physical education and ist evaluation, for the adults
    questions about life style, economic situation and job situation. The following results
    present some aspects of body concept in the student groups.</font></p>
    <p style="text-indent: 40; text-align: justify"><font size="2"><b>Results. </b>Three independent aspects of body
    concept are analyzed: evaluation, consciousness and external locus of control. All of
    these psychological dimensions were analyzed separately for the central body dimensions of
    physical fitness, health and physical appearance.</font></p>
    <p style="text-indent: 40; text-align: justify"><font size="2"><b>Discussion. </b>Results show that all groups are
    satisfied with all aspects of their body, but less with their fitness. Body consciousness
    is high in all analyzed aspects. The belief, that fitness or health are influenced by
    chance, is low in general, but higher for physical appearance. Comparisons between
    countries show a tendency of Czech students to evaluate all body aspects less positive
    than the others. The Russian students belief much more than the others that all body
    aspects are influenced by chance. It seems that the intercorrelations between evaluation,
    consciousness and locus of control are very complex and specific for the different aspects
    of the body and different cultures.</font></p>
    <p align="right"><font size="2"><i>Table 1</i></font></p>
